WEBVTT

00:00:00.460 --> 00:00:08.380
Hello and welcome back. In this lecture, I'm going to show you how to use Codex with radare2

00:00:08.380 --> 00:00:16.060
to solve crackme number 2, which is a GUI-based crackme. So head over to my crackme folder

00:00:16.780 --> 00:00:27.340
and run crackme2. You will see it will open up Windows GUI and ask you to input the serial

00:00:27.340 --> 00:00:35.980
number. Let us enter 123456 and click on the check button and it says

00:00:35.980 --> 00:00:41.320
wrong serial. So we will remember this string wrong serial and use the same

00:00:41.320 --> 00:00:49.780
strategy to solve this crackme. Now let's open our Codex. You can also use

00:00:49.780 --> 00:01:12.220
Claude Code if you have a Claude Code subscription. Let's click on new chat and

00:01:12.220 --> 00:01:21.030
close the sidebar. We will now get the README file. We will now get the skill

00:01:21.030 --> 00:01:34.320
file. So head over to the AI skills folder and copy the path to this skill

00:01:34.320 --> 00:01:44.460
file. Right-click Copy as Path, and then we give our prompt to Codex. Ask it to

00:01:44.460 --> 00:01:58.200
read this skill file and paste in the skill file. Then analyze this crackme

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:04.700
and then give it the path to the crackme. So we right-click and copy the path

00:02:04.700 --> 00:02:14.120
and paste the path in here. So we ask Codex to analyze this crackme to find

00:02:14.120 --> 00:02:33.140
the control flow logic which decides to show the string wrong serial and

00:02:33.140 --> 00:02:48.220
understand how it decides to show that string or any other string message then

00:02:48.220 --> 00:02:56.020
explain to me how it works. So this is the prompt. Read the skill file then

00:02:56.020 --> 00:03:01.000
analyze this crack me to find the control flow logic which decides to show

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:06.040
the string wrong serial and understand how it decides to show that string or

00:03:06.040 --> 00:03:13.840
any other string message. Then explain to me how it works. Then click on

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:24.140
Go. Make sure your GPT model is the highest one, which is at time of recording GPT 5.5,

00:03:24.700 --> 00:03:30.940
and make sure your reasoning effort is set to extra high. Extra high is needed because doing

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:39.980
reverse engineering does involve complex reasoning. So now it has gone to work and says that

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:55.970
it is reading the skill file first and straight away it has already found the interesting strings

00:03:55.970 --> 00:04:04.610
for example, CM2-91A7-2026, and also the congrats and the wrong serial messages. So let us copy this.

00:04:04.610 --> 00:04:13.890
This could be the password, the serial key, and we paste it in here and click Check, and congrats.

00:04:13.890 --> 00:04:21.120
It has managed to solve it for us so easily, but let us see what else it has to say.

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:23.480
And here is another confirmation.

00:04:23.480 --> 00:04:29.600
It says that the program compares the edit box text against the hardcoded string, which

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:38.250
is the serial key we just saw.

00:04:38.250 --> 00:04:40.870
And finally, it gives the report.

00:04:40.870 --> 00:04:46.090
It says the relevant logic is in this address here.

00:04:46.090 --> 00:04:49.450
And the valid serial is hardcoded as this.

00:04:49.450 --> 00:04:53.260
Another confirmation.

00:04:53.260 --> 00:04:59.500
And here it has got the core logic written down as pseudocode, which resembles C programming

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:02.640
language.

00:05:02.640 --> 00:05:09.740
So as you can see, it gets the text that the user inputs using this function, this API.

00:05:09.740 --> 00:05:18.020
It then uses the string compare function from C and it compares this string, this constant

00:05:18.020 --> 00:05:21.060
with the input from the user.

00:05:21.060 --> 00:05:25.500
And then if it is correct, it is the same. It will return 0.

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:28.920
And then 0 means that the strings are identical.

00:05:28.920 --> 00:05:29.920
That means success.

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:35.660
So it prints the window message, congrats, at the bottom of the window.

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:42.840
However, if the comparison fails, that means it's a wrong serial key, which means the key

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:48.760
that the user enters does not match this key, then it will do the else part and show the

00:05:48.760 --> 00:05:59.200
wrong serial message instead. So very efficient and very concise. So this is how useful using

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:04.620
Codex with radare2 can be. So that's all for this video. Thank you for watching.

